I have to disagree with your statement &quot;Energy doesn&#39;t have mass.&quot;

This is blatantly wrong. Any type of energy at all has mass, not just energy stored by rest mass due to interaction with the Higg&#39;s field or that which is stored via the strong force. 

Chemical bonds, electromagnetic potential energy, and kinetic energy all make mass from the proper reference frames. Any energy at all does.

&quot;What causes energy to have mass?&quot;
Energy doesn&#39;t have mass. It&#39;s related to mass in being stored in the mass of a particle until produced as heat, light, sound, etc. which are mass-less (E = mc^2). 
Mass itself comes from a particle&#39;s interaction with the gluon and Higgs fields, most of it coming from the gluon-facilitated bond between quarks called the &quot;strong force&quot;. It is this strong force where most of mass comes from.
